-- From: Inflatable Safety Tip Guide
('Inflatable Safety Tip Guide', 'Safety', E'## Inflatable Safety Tip Guide\n\nThis comprehensive guide covers the essential safety checks every operator must perform before, during, and after inflatable operations.\n\n### Wind & Weather Check\n- Check the weather forecast before every event\n- Monitor wind speeds throughout the day — do not operate above 25 mph winds\n- Watch for sudden weather changes including lightning, heavy rain, or hail\n- Have a written weather policy and communicate it to your team and clients\n\n### Setup\n- Inspect the setup area for debris, holes, slopes, and overhead hazards\n- Ensure adequate clearance on all sides of the inflatable (minimum 6 feet)\n- Place ground tarps or mats under the inflatable to protect the vinyl\n- Verify power source is adequate and cords are safely routed away from foot traffic\n- Confirm the blower is securely attached and the tube is properly sealed\n\n### Anchoring\n- Use appropriate anchoring for the surface type — stakes for grass, sandbags or water barrels for hard surfaces\n- Always use ALL anchor points — never skip any anchor point on the unit\n\n### Physical Inspection\n- Walk around the entire unit checking for tears, holes, loose seams, and worn areas\n- Verify all D-rings, straps, and buckles are intact and secure\n\n### Review Safety Rules & Agreement\n- Post visible safety rules signage at every event\n- Review safety rules with the client and all attendees\n- Have clients sign a safety agreement or waiver before use\n- Ensure an adult supervisor is present at all times during operation', true),

-- From: Safety Rules Poster
('Safety Rules for Inflatable Operations', 'Safety', E'## Safety Rules — Adult Supervision at All Times\n\nThese core safety rules must be posted and enforced at every event where inflatables are in operation. Print and display these rules prominently near each unit.\n\n### The 12 Essential Safety Rules\n\n1. **No toys inside the bounce house** — Foreign objects can cause injuries\n2. **No pets allowed** — Animals can damage equipment and injure children\n3. **Ensure inflatable is anchored** — All anchor points must be secured before use\n4. **Remove shoes and accessories** — Glasses, jewelry, and sharp objects must be removed\n5. **Do not operate in inclement weather** — Wind, rain, and lightning are serious hazards\n6. **Follow max capacity** — Never exceed the posted weight and occupant limits\n7. **No wrestling, tumbling, or flipping** — Rough play causes the majority of injuries\n8. **No climbing on netting walls** — Netting is not designed to support body weight\n9. **No food, drinks, gum, or silly string** — These create slip hazards and damage vinyl\n10. **Do not move the bounce house** — Never relocate a unit while inflated or occupied\n11. **No water or fire** — Keep all flames and water sources away from the unit\n12. **Do not allow kids to play behind the bounce house** — The blower area is a danger zone\n\n### Implementation Tips\n- Print these rules on a weatherproof sign for each unit\n- Review rules verbally with every client at setup\n- Include rules in your rental agreement and waiver\n- Train all staff to enforce these rules consistently', true),

-- From: Near Miss/Incident Report
('How to Properly Document Incidents and Near Misses', 'Safety', E'## How to Properly Document Incidents and Near Misses\n\nProper incident documentation protects your business, helps prevent future incidents, and demonstrates professionalism to clients and insurance providers.\n\n### When to File a Report\nFile a report for ANY of the following:\n- **Incident:** Any event where injury occurred or property was damaged\n- **Near Miss:** Any event that could have resulted in injury or damage but did not\n\nNear miss reporting is just as important as incident reporting — it helps you identify and fix hazards before someone gets hurt.\n\n### Required Information\nEvery report must capture:\n- **Type:** Near Miss or Incident (check one)\n- **Date and Time:** Exact date and time of the event\n- **Reporter Full Name:** Person completing the report\n- **Incident Address:** Full address where the event occurred\n- **Description:** Detailed account using the 5W1H method — Who was involved, What happened, When it occurred, Where exactly, Why it happened, and How it unfolded\n- **Type of Injury:** If applicable, describe the nature of the injury\n- **First Responder Status:** Was 911 or first responders called? (Yes/No)\n- **Injured Party Contact:** Full name and contact information of anyone injured\n- **Witness Information:** Names and contact details of all witnesses\n\n### Best Practices\n- Complete the report as soon as possible while details are fresh\n- Be factual and objective — avoid opinions or blame\n- Take photographs of the scene, equipment, and any injuries\n- Notify your insurance provider within 24 hours for any incident involving injury\n- Store all reports securely and review them quarterly to identify patterns', true),

-- From: Interview Questionnaire
('Interview Guide: Hiring the Right Team Members', 'HR & Hiring', E'## Interview Guide: Hiring the Right Team Members\n\nUse this structured interview guide to evaluate candidates consistently. Each category includes a question and guidance on what to look for in responses.\n\n### 1. Customer Service Focus\n**Question:** Tell me about a time you went above and beyond for a customer.\n**What to look for:** Genuine enthusiasm for helping people, specific examples, understanding that customer satisfaction drives the business.\n\n### 2. First Impression Mindset\n**Question:** How do you ensure you make a great first impression?\n**What to look for:** Awareness of appearance, punctuality, positive attitude, understanding that they represent the company brand.\n\n### 3. Reliability & Dependability\n**Question:** Describe a time when you had to show up even when you did not want to.\n**What to look for:** Commitment to showing up on time, understanding that the team depends on them, willingness to push through discomfort.\n\n### 4. Handling Responsibility\n**Question:** Tell me about a time you were trusted with an important task. How did you handle it?\n**What to look for:** Ownership mentality, attention to detail, follow-through, pride in doing quality work.\n\n### 5. Initiative\n**Question:** Give an example of a time you saw something that needed to be done and took action without being asked.\n**What to look for:** Proactive mindset, willingness to go beyond minimum requirements, problem-solving orientation.\n\n### 6. Teamwork\n**Question:** Describe a situation where you had to work closely with someone you did not get along with.\n**What to look for:** Maturity, ability to set aside personal differences, focus on the task, communication skills.\n\n### 7. Problem Solving in the Field\n**Question:** What would you do if something went wrong at an event and your manager was not available?\n**What to look for:** Calm under pressure, logical thinking, willingness to make decisions, understanding of when to escalate.\n\n### 8. Attention to Detail\n**Question:** How do you make sure you do not miss important steps in a process?\n**What to look for:** Use of checklists, systematic approach, double-checking work, understanding that details matter in safety.\n\n### 9. Work Ethic & Physical Demands\n**Question:** This job requires physical labor in all weather conditions. How do you handle that?\n**What to look for:** Realistic expectations, physical fitness awareness, positive attitude toward hard work, experience with outdoor labor.\n\n### 10. Ownership & Accountability\n**Question:** Tell me about a time you made a mistake. How did you handle it?\n**What to look for:** Honesty, willingness to admit fault, focus on learning and improvement, no blame-shifting.', true),

-- From: Training Tracking Log
('Training Certification Tracking Best Practices', 'Training', E'## Training Certification Tracking Best Practices\n\nMaintaining current training certifications for your entire team is essential for safety compliance, insurance requirements, and professional operations.\n\n### What to Track\nFor each team member, maintain records of:\n- **Employee Name** and role\n- **Training/Certification Type** (e.g., SIOTO Safety Certification, CPR/First Aid, Equipment Operation)\n- **Completion Date** — When the training was completed\n- **Expiration Date** — When the certification expires\n- **Notes** — Any special conditions, restrictions, or follow-up needed\n\n### Best Practices\n- **Review monthly:** Set a recurring calendar reminder to review all certifications\n- **30-day renewal window:** Schedule renewal training at least 30 days before expiration\n- **No expired certifications in the field:** Never allow a team member with an expired certification to work unsupervised\n- **New hire onboarding:** Ensure all required certifications are completed before the first solo assignment\n- **Digital backup:** Keep both physical and digital copies of all certificates\n- **Audit readiness:** Organize records so they can be produced quickly for insurance audits or inspections\n\n### Recommended Training Categories\n- SIOTO Safety Certification\n- CPR/First Aid\n- Equipment Setup & Takedown\n- Customer Service & Communication\n- Emergency Response Procedures\n- Vehicle & Trailer Operation\n- Weather Safety Protocols', true),

-- From: A Day In The Life
('First Day Training & Evaluation Guide', 'Training', E'## First Day Training & Evaluation Guide\n\nThe first day on the job sets the tone for a new team member''s entire career with your company. Use this structured evaluation to ensure new hires are properly assessed and supported.\n\n### Safety & Professionalism (Evaluate These 5 Areas)\n1. Did the trainee follow all safety steps during setup and operation?\n2. Can the trainee identify situations where they should refuse to set up (unsafe conditions, inadequate space, weather concerns)?\n3. Did the trainee demonstrate professionalism in appearance and communication?\n4. Did the trainee properly inspect equipment before and after use?\n5. Did the trainee follow proper anchoring and securing procedures?\n\n### Customer Experience & Success\n1. How did the trainee handle a difficult or demanding customer?\n2. How does the trainee define a successful event delivery?\n\n### Trainee Reflection (Have Them Answer)\n1. What surprised you most about the job today?\n2. What areas do you feel you need to grow in?\n3. Are you clear on what is expected of you going forward?\n\n### Manager Review\nRate the trainee on:\n- [ ] Engagement and enthusiasm level\n- [ ] Adherence to safety standards\n- [ ] Ability to handle physical demands\n- [ ] Understanding of role expectations\n\n**Manager Comments:** Document specific observations, strengths, and areas for improvement.\n\n### Follow-Up Actions\n- Schedule a check-in after the first week\n- Assign a mentor or buddy for the first month\n- Review and discuss this evaluation with the trainee within 48 hours', true),

-- From: Manager Observation Form
('Manager Field Observation Guide', 'Operations', E'## Manager Field Observation Guide\n\nRegular field observations help maintain quality standards, identify training gaps, and recognize top performers. Use this guide to conduct structured evaluations of your team in the field.\n\n### Observation Categories\n\n**Safety Compliance**\n- Is the employee following all safety protocols?\n- Are proper anchoring procedures being used?\n- Is the employee monitoring weather conditions?\n- Are safety rules posted and being enforced?\n\n**Customer Interaction**\n- Is the employee greeting customers professionally?\n- Are customer questions being answered accurately?\n- Is the employee maintaining a positive attitude?\n- Are complaints being handled appropriately?\n\n**Equipment Handling**\n- Is equipment being set up correctly and efficiently?\n- Is the employee performing pre-use inspections?\n- Is equipment being properly cleaned and stored after use?\n- Are any equipment issues being reported promptly?\n\n**Professionalism**\n- Is the employee in proper uniform/attire?\n- Is the employee punctual and prepared?\n- Is the employee representing the company brand positively?\n\n**Communication**\n- Is the employee communicating effectively with the team?\n- Are issues being escalated appropriately?\n- Is the employee providing clear instructions to customers?\n\n### Scoring & Follow-Up\n- Rate each category on a scale of 1-5\n- Document specific examples for any score below 3\n- Create action items for improvement areas\n- Schedule follow-up observation within 30 days for any employee scoring below average\n- Recognize and reward employees who consistently score 4-5', true);


