-- SOPs (Standard Operating Procedures)
-- ============================================================


('Inflatable Setup & Safety SOP', 'Safety', E'## Standard Operating Procedure: Inflatable Setup & Safety\n\n### Purpose\nTo ensure consistent, safe setup and operation of all inflatable units at every event.\n\n### Scope\nApplies to all team members involved in inflatable setup, operation, and takedown.\n\n### Procedure\n\n**Pre-Event (Day Before)**\n1. Check weather forecast for event day\n2. Confirm all equipment is loaded and inventory is complete\n3. Verify vehicle is fueled and maintenance is current\n\n**Arrival & Setup**\n1. Arrive at least 60 minutes before event start time\n2. Inspect the setup area for debris, holes, slopes, and overhead hazards\n3. Ensure minimum 6 feet clearance on all sides\n4. Lay ground tarps or mats\n5. Unroll and position the inflatable unit\n6. Connect blower and verify secure attachment\n7. Inflate the unit and perform full physical inspection\n8. Anchor using ALL anchor points — stakes for grass, sandbags for hard surfaces\n9. Post safety rules signage\n10. Review safety rules with client\n11. Collect signed waiver/safety agreement\n\n**During Operation**\n1. Maintain adult supervision at all times\n2. Enforce all 12 safety rules\n3. Monitor weather conditions continuously\n4. Check anchor points every 30 minutes\n5. Monitor occupancy — never exceed max capacity\n\n**Takedown**\n1. Ensure all participants have exited\n2. Turn off and disconnect blower\n3. Remove all anchoring\n4. Clean and sanitize the unit\n5. Deflate, fold, and roll properly\n6. Load equipment and verify nothing is left behind\n7. Complete post-event inspection report', true),

('Incident Response SOP', 'Safety', E'## Standard Operating Procedure: Incident Response\n\n### Purpose\nTo ensure proper handling of any incident or near miss during operations.\n\n### Scope\nApplies to all team members present at any event.\n\n### Procedure\n\n**Immediate Response (First 5 Minutes)**\n1. Ensure the safety of all participants — stop operations if necessary\n2. Assess the situation — determine if medical attention is needed\n3. Call 911 if there is any injury requiring medical attention\n4. Administer first aid if trained and appropriate\n5. Secure the area to prevent further incidents\n\n**Documentation (Within 1 Hour)**\n1. Complete a Near Miss/Incident Report form\n2. Record: Type (Near Miss or Incident), Date, Time, Location\n3. Document full description using 5W1H method (Who, What, When, Where, Why, How)\n4. Record type of injury if applicable\n5. Note whether first responders were called\n6. Collect contact information for injured party\n7. Collect contact information for all witnesses\n8. Take photographs of the scene, equipment, and any injuries\n\n**Notification (Within 24 Hours)**\n1. Notify your direct supervisor/manager immediately\n2. Notify the company owner within 4 hours\n3. Contact insurance provider within 24 hours for any injury incident\n4. File report in the company incident tracking system\n\n**Follow-Up (Within 1 Week)**\n1. Review the incident with the full team\n2. Identify root cause and contributing factors\n3. Implement corrective actions to prevent recurrence\n4. Update SOPs or checklists if needed\n5. Follow up with injured party if applicable', true),

('Pre-Season Preparation SOP', 'Operations', E'## Standard Operating Procedure: Pre-Season Preparation\n\n### Purpose\nTo ensure the business is fully prepared before the busy season begins.\n\n### Scope\nApplies to business owners and managers responsible for seasonal operations.\n\n### Procedure\n\n**Personnel (8-12 Weeks Before Season)**\n1. Begin hiring process — post job openings on Social Media, Job Boards, Colleges, and Universities\n2. Contact staff from last year to confirm availability\n3. Prepare interview questionnaire using the SIOTO Interview Guide\n4. Develop training and onboarding plan\n5. Schedule SIOTO Safety Training for all team members (group pricing available)\n6. Complete all training certifications before first event\n\n**Tools & Equipment (6-8 Weeks Before Season)**\n1. Inventory all blowers (1HP, 1.5HP, 2HP) and order replacements\n2. Stock sandbags, stakes, and clips\n3. Stock tarps and mats\n4. Inspect all dollies and repair/replace as needed\n5. Test all portable generators and schedule maintenance\n6. Stock cleaning materials (rags, spray bottles, cleaners, disinfectants)\n7. Inspect, maintain, and repair all units (inflatables, dunk tanks, games, foam machines, concessions)\n8. Stock supplies for concession machines\n\n**Vehicles & Trailers (4-6 Weeks Before Season)**\n1. Schedule vehicle maintenance (oil change, tire rotations, etc.)\n2. Verify Registration and Insurance Card in each vehicle\n3. Install/activate Toll Pass in each vehicle\n4. Stock breakdown tools in each vehicle\n5. Verify license plates are current on all vehicles\n6. Inspect trailers and schedule repairs\n7. Stock ratchet straps and tie-down straps\n\n**Final Checks (2 Weeks Before Season)**\n1. Complete all checklist items above\n2. Conduct team meeting to review SOPs and safety procedures\n3. Run a practice setup/takedown with the full team\n4. Verify insurance coverage is current and adequate\n5. Test all booking and scheduling systems', true);
